
The i370 compiler
-----------------
This directory contains code for building a compiler for the
32-bit ESA/390 architecture. It is NOT for the 64-bit z/Architecture
systems; it explicitly avoids generating any instructions that weren't
generally available for System/390. The (misleadingly named) s390
compiler is for use with the z/Architecture; it does NOT support the
older S/390 systems.

This compiler supports two different styles of assembly:

-- HLASM-style assembly code.  Can be assembled with standard HLASM.
   The current binutils/gas assembler is now sufficiently compatible
   with HLASM to be able to assemble the resulting output.
-- SVR4-style assembly. Conforming to the System V Release 4 specs for
   the various section names and pseudo-op names that are generated.
   Designed specifically for the earliest binutils/gas implementation.

Multiple operating system targets are supported:
-- MVS, Open Edition (USS Unix System Services), VSE, DIGNUS, PDOSGB,
   and several other MVS-like variants. These all generate HLASM-style
   assembly, and differ primarily in how function linkage is handled:
   the function prologs and epilogs differ between all of these. Some
   use IBM-supplied macros, and some do not.
-- Linux. This requires the assembler to generate ELF format binaries,
   and thus forces the use of SVR4-style assembly.

Currently, these targets are supported by recompiling the cmpiler with
different #define settings. These should be replaced by run-time flags.


Cross-compiling Hints
---------------------
When building a cross-compiler on AIX, set the environment variable CC
and be sure to set the -ma and -qcpluscmt flags; i.e.

   export CC="cc -ma -qcpluscmt"

do this *before* running configure, e.g.

   configure --target=i370-ibm-linux --prefix=/where/to/install/usr

The Objective-C and FORTRAN front ends don't build.  To avoid looking at
errors, do only

   make LANGUAGES=c


OpenEdition Hints
-----------------
The shell script "install" is handy for users of OpenEdition.


The ELF ABI
-----------
This compiler, in conjunction with the gas/binutils assembler, defines
a defacto ELF-based ABI for the ESA/390 architecture.  Be warned: this
ABI is experimental.  It is subject to change.  You should not commit
to major software systems without further exploring and understanding
ABI issues.

Here are some of the known issues:

-- All arguments are currently passed on the callee stack. They really
   should be moved to the caller stack.

-- A large variety of performance gains might be gotten by redesigning
   the guts of i370.md.

ELF ABI PIC Overview
--------------------
The -fPIC flag should produce position independent code.  By specifying
this flag, address constants are stored in the data section, instead of
the text section, allowing them to be adjusted during a dynamic/runtime
load.  Addressing is established using r12 as base pointer in the data
section. It can be thought of as a table-of-contents (TOC) entry.

In the (non-PIC, non-shared) application:
```
.text
caller:
  L  r15,=A(callee)
  BASR  r14,r15

.data
callee:
  ST r12,68(,sp)
  L  r12,12(,r15)
  BR r12
  .short   0
  .long callee.textentry
  .long callee.literalpool
  .long callee.pagetable
  .using   callee.literalpool,r12

```
In the PIC shared library:
```
.text
callee.textentry:
  L  r12,16(,r15)
  ... main body of callee routine ...

.data
callee.literalpool:
  .ltorg
```

The idea here is that r15 is used in the branch and link (BASR) to
establish r15.  But r15 is used to address a pseudo-TOC entry in the
data section. The pseudo-TOC entry contains the real address of the
text to be called, and a pointer to the first literal pool for that
routine.  Additional literal pools are chained as needed.

A more detailed explanation can be found in the `i370.c` file.

ChangeLog
---------
Oct98-Dec98 -- add ELF back end; work on getting ABI more or less functional.
98.12.05 -- fix numerous MVC bugs
99.02.06 -- multiply insn sometimes not generated when needed.
         -- extendsidi bugs, bad literal values printed
         -- remove broken adddi subdi patterns
99.02.15 -- add clrstrsi pattern
         -- fix -O2 divide bug
99.03.04 -- base & index reg usage bugs
99.03.15 -- fixes for returning long longs and structs (struct value return)
99.03.29 -- fix handling & alignment of shorts
99.03.31 -- clobbered register 14 is not always clobbered
99.04.02 -- operand constraints for cmphi
99.04.07 -- function pointer fixes for call, call_value patterns,
            function pointers derefed once too often.
99.04.14 -- add pattern to print double-wide int
         -- check intval<4096 for misc operands
         -- add clrstrsi pattern
         -- movstrsi fixes
99.04.16 -- use r2 to pass args into r11 in subroutine call.
         -- fixes to movsi; some operand combinations impossible;
            rework constraints
         -- start work on forward jump optimization
         -- char alignment bug
99.04.25 -- add untyped_call pattern so that builtin_apply works
99.04.27 -- fixes to compare logical under mask
99.04.28 -- reg 2 is clobbered by calls
99.04.30 -- fix rare mulsi bug
99.04.30 -- add constraints so that all RS, SI, SS forms insns have valid
            addressing modes
99.04.30 -- major condition code fixes. The old code was just way off
            w.r.t. which insns set condition code, and the codes that
            were set.  The extent of this damage was unbelievable.
99.05.01 -- restructuring of operand constraints on many patterns,
            many lead to invalid instructions being genned.
99.05.02 -- float pt fixes
         -- fix movdi issue bugs
99.05.03 -- fix divide insn; was dividing incorrectly
99.05.05 -- fix sign extension problems on andhi
         -- deprecate some constraints
99.05.06 -- add set_attr insn lengths; fix misc litpool sizes
         -- add notes about how unsigned jumps work (i.e.
            arithmetic vs. logical vs. signed vs unsigned).
99.05.11 -- use insn length to predict forward branch target;
            use relative branching where possible,
            remove un-needed base register reload.
99.05.15 -- fix movstrsi, clrstrsi, cmpstrsi patterns as per conversation
            w/ Richard Henderson.
1999-2024 -- Variety of fixes from Paul Edwards, Dave Pitts and many
            others, for a variety of issues (documented only in private
            CVS trees). Examples include support for copying data of
            arbitrary size (including more than 256 bytes) i.e. memcpy.
Sept,Oct 2024 -- 25th Anniversary Edition: Merge the various different
            fixes that have been provided into a *single* git-based
            repo. These fixes have been tested on the Linux-2.2.1
            kernel, the PDCLIB C library, the uClibc-ng C library, and
            BusyBox. And by double-cross-compiling the assembler and
            compiler itself.  These all work. I'm told PDOS works also.
